01:01:25.152 --> 01:01:27.110
well, you talked about
your process in the book

01:01:27.110 --> 01:01:28.776
a little bit about
how you were writing.

01:01:28.776 --> 01:01:30.380
And it's clear from
your other books,

01:01:30.380 --> 01:01:33.980
too, that you write from
a place of vulnerability

01:01:33.980 --> 01:01:36.960
to like invite your
readers to join you.

01:01:36.960 --> 01:01:39.020
And I was wondering,
because psychedelics

01:01:39.020 --> 01:01:45.050
are such a vulnerable
experience, the theme of this

01:01:45.050 --> 01:01:46.760
is writing the
ineffable, and I'm

01:01:46.760 --> 01:01:49.730
wondering, for bare
bones process-wise,

01:01:49.730 --> 01:01:51.340
how did this differ for you?

01:01:51.340 --> 01:01:54.230
What was your process like
for writing this book compared

01:01:54.230 --> 01:01:57.410
to Botany of Desire or
Omnivore's Dilemma or even

01:01:57.410 --> 01:01:59.570
your books on architecture?

01:01:59.570 --> 01:02:01.240
Yeah, I don't know
that the process

01:02:01.240 --> 01:02:02.510
was fundamentally different.

01:02:02.510 --> 01:02:06.200
I think what you're saying about
vulnerability is interesting.

01:02:06.200 --> 01:02:11.980
I like to write from a position
of naivete or ignorance.

01:02:11.980 --> 01:02:14.040
And almost everything
I've written,

01:02:14.040 --> 01:02:17.140
if you read the first paragraph
or two, I'm kind of an idiot,

01:02:17.140 --> 01:02:19.680
and I don't know things.

01:02:19.680 --> 01:02:23.290
And I realized I
really like writing

01:02:23.290 --> 01:02:25.180
at the beginning of
the learning curve

01:02:25.180 --> 01:02:27.490
rather than at the
end as an expert.

01:02:27.490 --> 01:02:30.190
And most of us, especially
most of us in academia,

01:02:30.190 --> 01:02:33.010
we don't start writing until
we've got it all figured out.

01:02:33.010 --> 01:02:36.190
And we impersonate
the person who has

01:02:36.190 --> 01:02:38.440
it all figured out on page one.

01:02:38.440 --> 01:02:41.740
And I've always found
that a bit of a turnoff.

01:02:41.740 --> 01:02:47.410
And I think the reader likes
to go on a journey with you

01:02:47.410 --> 01:02:48.610
of learning.

01:02:48.610 --> 01:02:52.180
So this book, like
all my books, begins

01:02:52.180 --> 01:02:56.080
in a state of ignorance,
relatively, and curiosity,

01:02:56.080 --> 01:02:59.110
and that we're going to
learn all this together.

01:02:59.110 --> 01:03:02.420
And I think that's generally
a good writing strategy.

01:03:02.420 --> 01:03:05.320
I think it's awkward for the
academic for various reasons

01:03:05.320 --> 01:03:10.720
having to do with conventions,
and that that vulnerability

01:03:10.720 --> 01:03:13.340
is not welcome in academia.

01:03:16.450 --> 01:03:17.980
But in general, it was similar.

01:03:17.980 --> 01:03:22.780
It was kind of like I'm going
to learn everything I can.

01:03:22.780 --> 01:03:24.310
I've got a file called science.

01:03:24.310 --> 01:03:25.840
I've got a file called history.

01:03:25.840 --> 01:03:28.270
I've got a file called memoir.

01:03:28.270 --> 01:03:31.330
And I'm going to fill
those up, and then

01:03:31.330 --> 01:03:32.950
figure out how to layer them.

01:03:32.950 --> 01:03:35.060
The big difference is--

01:03:35.060 --> 01:03:37.840
and this is maybe getting
a little too granular--

01:03:37.840 --> 01:03:41.230
is that most of my
books, each chapter

01:03:41.230 --> 01:03:44.980
has had the multiplication
of perspectives in it.

01:03:44.980 --> 01:03:47.440
So in Botany of Desire there's
a chapter on the apple,

01:03:47.440 --> 01:03:49.330
and you learn about
Johnny Appleseed,

01:03:49.330 --> 01:03:51.440
and you learn about the
biology of the apple tree

01:03:51.440 --> 01:03:54.340
and my own experiences
and da da da da da.

01:03:54.340 --> 01:03:57.190
Here I couldn't do
that for some reason.

01:03:57.190 --> 01:04:01.030
There was the psychedelics,
and the experience

01:04:01.030 --> 01:04:03.640
and the science of
it, and each chapter

01:04:03.640 --> 01:04:07.130
had to be a different lens.

01:04:07.130 --> 01:04:08.850
And I'm not sure
exactly why that was.

01:04:08.850 --> 01:04:11.030
It was something about
the nature of the subject.

01:04:11.030 --> 01:04:12.703
But it wasn't
fundamentally different.

01:04:12.703 --> 01:04:14.062
Thanks

01:04:14.062 --> 01:04:16.131
Thanks.

