01:05:32.800 --> 01:05:34.170
It was just too--

01:05:34.170 --> 01:05:37.170
I did bring my computer
into one session,

01:05:37.170 --> 01:05:39.960
and that was a huge mistake.

01:05:39.960 --> 01:05:41.820
I had wanted to
perform an experiment

01:05:41.820 --> 01:05:45.490
that I'd heard about, which was
the rotating mask experiment.

01:05:45.490 --> 01:05:47.940
There's this famous
experiment in psychology

01:05:47.940 --> 01:05:51.760
of a mask that's convex on one
side and concave on the other,

01:05:51.760 --> 01:05:52.682
and it rotates.

01:05:52.682 --> 01:05:54.390
And something really
interesting happens.

01:05:54.390 --> 01:05:58.200
As you begin to
perceive the back of it,

01:05:58.200 --> 01:06:00.960
it pops out because the
brain will not allow

01:06:00.960 --> 01:06:03.930
you to see a concave face.

01:06:03.930 --> 01:06:05.520
Faces are convex.

01:06:05.520 --> 01:06:07.950
And it's an example of what's
called predictive coding,

01:06:07.950 --> 01:06:09.690
the fact that most
of what we see

01:06:09.690 --> 01:06:15.450
is a prediction rather
than literal sensory data.

01:06:15.450 --> 01:06:19.230
And I'd heard that people on
psychedelics, it didn't happen.

01:06:19.230 --> 01:06:20.730
They could see the
back of the mask.

01:06:20.730 --> 01:06:22.563
And it's true of
schizophrenics, apparently.

01:06:22.563 --> 01:06:24.120
They can see the
back of the mask.

01:06:24.120 --> 01:06:32.889
So this very important brain
function, I wanted to test it.

01:06:32.889 --> 01:06:34.680
And I thought I would
take some notes, too.

01:06:34.680 --> 01:06:38.010
The mere act of having
the computer in the room--

01:06:38.010 --> 01:06:40.000
Leary famously talked
about set and setting,

01:06:40.000 --> 01:06:45.610
that the experiences is highly
vulnerable to your expectations

01:06:45.610 --> 01:06:47.550
and the environment you're in.

01:06:50.160 --> 01:06:54.210
Half of this experience was
this horrible computer world,

01:06:54.210 --> 01:06:56.640
where the graphics
of that mask became

01:06:56.640 --> 01:06:58.950
the graphics I
experienced, and the music

01:06:58.950 --> 01:07:01.800
summoned this video game
world that I hated and I

01:07:01.800 --> 01:07:04.170
felt trapped in for hours.

01:07:04.170 --> 01:07:07.170
So I never brought my
computer into the room again.

01:07:07.170 --> 01:07:12.540
And I felt like to write
notes during the experience

01:07:12.540 --> 01:07:18.180
would represent not
completely surrendering to it,

01:07:18.180 --> 01:07:20.070
which all my guides
had said was really

01:07:20.070 --> 01:07:21.830
the key to a
successful experience,

01:07:21.830 --> 01:07:24.800
is not to fight
anything about it.

01:07:24.800 --> 01:07:27.300
If you see a monster, you're
supposed to step right up to it

01:07:27.300 --> 01:07:29.160
and ask what it's
doing in your brain.

01:07:29.160 --> 01:07:33.630
If you see a staircase,
you're supposed to climb it.

01:07:33.630 --> 01:07:35.350
You know, John Lennon said it.

01:07:35.350 --> 01:07:37.380
Relax your mind and
float downstream.

01:07:37.380 --> 01:07:39.690
And taking notes
didn't go with that.

01:07:39.690 --> 01:07:43.800
So what I did instead was
I asked my guides to record

01:07:43.800 --> 01:07:47.190
anything I said, and I would
try to say a few things to them,

01:07:47.190 --> 01:07:56.130
which never was better than,
like, spectacular, or gnomic

01:07:56.130 --> 01:08:00.464
utterances like, I don't want to
be so stingy with my feelings.

01:08:00.464 --> 01:08:01.130
That was a note.

01:08:03.690 --> 01:08:05.340
So that wasn't that helpful.

01:08:05.340 --> 01:08:07.410
But what I did
do-- and actually,

01:08:07.410 --> 01:08:10.290
what the guides, both
in the university

01:08:10.290 --> 01:08:12.960
trials and the
underground experiences,

01:08:12.960 --> 01:08:15.390
tell you is write a
journal right after.

01:08:15.390 --> 01:08:18.250
So that night I did two things.

01:08:18.250 --> 01:08:22.880
One was Judith debriefed
me over dinner,

01:08:22.880 --> 01:08:26.430
and I said as much as I
could about the experience.

01:08:26.430 --> 01:08:27.930
And that was actually
really helpful

01:08:27.930 --> 01:08:31.080
because she could connect
it to other things

01:08:31.080 --> 01:08:34.560
and had various insights,
because what you're doing

01:08:34.560 --> 01:08:37.020
is you're taking something
that's non-linear,

01:08:37.020 --> 01:08:40.590
non-narrative, and you're trying
to turn it into a narrative.

01:08:40.590 --> 01:08:42.055
And you are doing
violence to it,

01:08:42.055 --> 01:08:44.430
in a way, because there's tons
of it that makes no sense,

01:08:44.430 --> 01:08:46.770
and you're kind of
editing that out.

01:08:46.770 --> 01:08:51.060
And then I would write this
long, loose journal that

01:08:51.060 --> 01:08:53.640
would be like 15 single
spaced pages of everything

01:08:53.640 --> 01:08:56.430
I could remember
about the experience.

01:08:56.430 --> 01:08:58.750
And that became the
raw material later.

01:08:58.750 --> 01:09:01.260
But one of the things that's
striking about the experience

01:09:01.260 --> 01:09:03.930
is you don't have
trouble remembering it.

01:09:03.930 --> 01:09:07.470
It's not like dreams, where you
feel that undertow pulling it

01:09:07.470 --> 01:09:09.870
out of your conscious
awareness and you have

01:09:09.870 --> 01:09:12.189
to fight it to preserve it.

01:09:12.189 --> 01:09:15.420
I've talked to people
who can vividly recall

01:09:15.420 --> 01:09:18.010
trips they had 30 years ago.

01:09:18.010 --> 01:09:20.649
It's just stored in the memory
in a very different way.

01:09:20.649 --> 01:09:25.420
But anyway, I used these
journals, and that was the key.

