I'm much more interested in
continuing this exploration

01:10:38.560 --> 01:10:40.790
of self and consciousness.

01:10:40.790 --> 01:10:41.960
I don't know where it goes.

01:10:41.960 --> 01:10:43.690
But one of the
things I learned is

01:10:43.690 --> 01:10:45.670
that there are many
other ways to explore

01:10:45.670 --> 01:10:47.980
this besides psychedelics,
meditation being

01:10:47.980 --> 01:10:50.230
a very important one,
and meditation being

01:10:50.230 --> 01:10:53.110
the way many people keep
their psychedelic experiences

01:10:53.110 --> 01:10:55.190
alive for themselves.

01:10:55.190 --> 01:10:59.980
There's a very interesting
progression from psychedelics

01:10:59.980 --> 01:11:04.030
to Buddhism that many, many
Americans have followed,

01:11:04.030 --> 01:11:05.350
and there's a logic to that.

01:11:05.350 --> 01:11:08.380
And the brain networks are
affected in similar ways.

01:11:08.380 --> 01:11:11.620
So I'm kind of more interested
in that general area.

01:11:11.620 --> 01:11:13.095
But I have no idea.

01:11:13.095 --> 01:11:13.720
I have no idea.

01:11:13.720 --> 01:11:17.310
What I normally do between books
is write a couple articles,

01:11:17.310 --> 01:11:20.110
and then one of
them turns out to be

01:11:20.110 --> 01:11:23.650
a bottomless well of
stuff I have to learn,

01:11:23.650 --> 01:11:25.390
and I realized
that's the next book.

01:11:25.390 --> 01:11:27.842
But I don't know what is yet.

01:11:27.842 --> 01:11:30.300
I will keep my eye on The New
Yorker and The New York Times

01:11:30.300 --> 01:11:31.633
Magazine and look forward to it.

01:11:31.633 --> 01:11:32.310
Thank you.

01:11:32.310 --> 01:11:35.040
Thank you.

01:11:35.040 --> 01:11:36.290
Thanks very much for the book.

01:11:36.290 --> 01:11:38.290
I enjoyed it.

01:11:38.290 --> 01:11:40.850
We're at Harvard, and you
just mentioned Timothy Leary.

01:11:40.850 --> 01:11:45.710
And so I'd like to pursue
that a little bit more.

01:11:45.710 --> 01:11:49.610
Those of us who were involved
in psychedelics way back

01:11:49.610 --> 01:11:53.450
then in the '60s, when Timothy
Leary was walking among us,

01:11:53.450 --> 01:11:55.340
believe that you
give everybody acid

01:11:55.340 --> 01:11:58.970
and we'll have universal peace.

01:11:58.970 --> 01:12:02.180
And what you've described, and
what we're talking about here,

01:12:02.180 --> 01:12:06.350
is a very individual,
very personal experience.

01:12:06.350 --> 01:12:09.800
But we're doing it in the
context of a center, which

01:12:09.800 --> 01:12:12.380
I imagine is concerned
about the planet, concerned

01:12:12.380 --> 01:12:13.550
about the environment.

01:12:13.550 --> 01:12:15.920
Is there potential
in psychedelics

01:12:15.920 --> 01:12:19.100
for redressing, repairing
our relationship

01:12:19.100 --> 01:12:23.600
with the environment as a
society beyond the individual?

01:12:23.600 --> 01:12:28.210
I think that's a great question,
and a great question to end on.

01:12:28.210 --> 01:12:31.750
You know, a lot of people who do
this research, even university

01:12:31.750 --> 01:12:35.440
researchers,
psychopharmacologists

01:12:35.440 --> 01:12:39.100
and pharmacologists, come out of
this work thinking this really

01:12:39.100 --> 01:12:41.372
does have relevance
for our predicament.

01:12:41.372 --> 01:12:43.830
And they're a little nervous
about talking that way because

01:12:43.830 --> 01:12:45.970
of Timothy Leary.

01:12:45.970 --> 01:12:49.840
But many people emerge
from the experience

01:12:49.840 --> 01:12:53.704
with that conviction, that it
has something to offer us now.

01:12:53.704 --> 01:12:55.120
And I don't think
it's an accident

01:12:55.120 --> 01:12:58.240
that this revival of research
is happening right now.

01:13:01.030 --> 01:13:03.180
There's two ways
to look at this.

01:13:03.180 --> 01:13:08.610
I do believe that, from
my own experience and also

01:13:08.610 --> 01:13:10.410
from the research,
that the nature

01:13:10.410 --> 01:13:14.820
of the psychedelic experience
has a very specific relevance

01:13:14.820 --> 01:13:17.700
for what I see as the two
biggest problems that face us

01:13:17.700 --> 01:13:19.530
as a civilization.

01:13:19.530 --> 01:13:24.660
One is tribalism and the other
is the environmental crisis.

01:13:24.660 --> 01:13:28.230
And in this sense,
both are based

01:13:28.230 --> 01:13:32.030
on the objectifying of
the other and of building

01:13:32.030 --> 01:13:36.500
walls rather than
bridges, and that

01:13:36.500 --> 01:13:40.100
the psychedelic experience,
because of the fact

01:13:40.100 --> 01:13:44.900
that it can lead to this ego
dissolution and the opening

01:13:44.900 --> 01:13:48.440
of these channels of connection,
this sense of connection

01:13:48.440 --> 01:13:53.180
is the most powerful thing
that comes out of it.

01:13:53.180 --> 01:13:56.320
Some of the researchers have
even sought to measure this,

01:13:56.320 --> 01:13:58.520
and there is a
scale psychologists

01:13:58.520 --> 01:14:01.940
have called nature
connectedness, where

01:14:01.940 --> 01:14:03.140
they actually--

01:14:03.140 --> 01:14:08.180
going back to your
question-- they assess,

01:14:08.180 --> 01:14:10.130
through a
questionnaire, how much

01:14:10.130 --> 01:14:14.440
do you feel you're in
nature or outside of nature?

01:14:14.440 --> 01:14:17.320
And people's scales
change dramatically

01:14:17.320 --> 01:14:20.230
after a psychedelic experience.

01:14:20.230 --> 01:14:25.540
And that doesn't surprise me
at all that that would happen.

01:14:25.540 --> 01:14:29.080
My guess is if you did a similar
scale for how tribal you feel,

01:14:29.080 --> 01:14:31.910
how much you feel
that your group is

01:14:31.910 --> 01:14:35.140
no different than the other--

01:14:35.140 --> 01:14:37.480
because those two things are
growing from the same place

01:14:37.480 --> 01:14:40.210
of objectification.

01:14:40.210 --> 01:14:45.700
So if these drugs have the power
to address those two problems,

01:14:45.700 --> 01:14:52.630
then you get to another
huge challenge which is,

01:14:52.630 --> 01:14:55.000
how do you prescribe
a drug for a culture?

01:14:55.000 --> 01:14:56.560
You can't.

01:14:56.560 --> 01:14:58.510
I mean, Timothy
Leary tried to do it.

01:14:58.510 --> 01:15:00.970
He would make
calculations on napkins

01:15:00.970 --> 01:15:03.910
about how many Americans
he'd have to turn on

01:15:03.910 --> 01:15:07.750
to change America, and
it was like 2.9 million,

01:15:07.750 --> 01:15:09.490
or 1.9 million.

01:15:09.490 --> 01:15:11.110
Well, that many
people were turned on

01:15:11.110 --> 01:15:14.980
and everything didn't change.

01:15:14.980 --> 01:15:17.720
You're not going to
put it in the water.

01:15:17.720 --> 01:15:20.560
It's not like fluoride.

01:15:20.560 --> 01:15:23.980
So that's where you
run into trouble.

01:15:23.980 --> 01:15:26.530
And that was a
debate in the '50s.

01:15:26.530 --> 01:15:31.210
The goal was, if these drugs did
have a positive social effect--

01:15:31.210 --> 01:15:32.800
and Huxley believed this, too.

01:15:32.800 --> 01:15:36.310
Many, many people believed
this during the '50s and '60s--

01:15:36.310 --> 01:15:39.280
how do you spread those ideas?

01:15:39.280 --> 01:15:42.640
Leary's theory was
turn on everybody.

01:15:42.640 --> 01:15:43.900
He was a Democrat.

01:15:43.900 --> 01:15:46.300
He was the populist
of psychedelics.

01:15:46.300 --> 01:15:49.870
Huxley and several other people
that he was affiliated with,

01:15:49.870 --> 01:15:53.170
researchers, were
terrified by this idea,

01:15:53.170 --> 01:15:55.090
and they had a much
more Mandarin approach.

01:15:55.090 --> 01:15:57.820
You turn on the elite.

01:15:57.820 --> 01:16:00.020
And there were efforts
to turn on the elite.

01:16:00.020 --> 01:16:03.980
That's how it got into Silicon
Valley, artists, writers,

01:16:03.980 --> 01:16:08.230
politicians, people
in the church.

01:16:08.230 --> 01:16:09.940
And there was a
deliberate effort--

01:16:09.940 --> 01:16:11.290
I talk about it in the book--

01:16:11.290 --> 01:16:13.450
to turn on these
people with the thought

01:16:13.450 --> 01:16:15.340
that this new kind
of consciousness

01:16:15.340 --> 01:16:17.320
would filter down.

01:16:17.320 --> 01:16:19.780
That didn't really work, either.

01:16:19.780 --> 01:16:21.850
But the possibility is there.

01:16:21.850 --> 01:16:25.450
And we can all think
of an individual

01:16:25.450 --> 01:16:30.430
who really would benefit
from a psychedelic trip.

01:16:30.430 --> 01:16:34.480
But it actually wouldn't
work because you really

01:16:34.480 --> 01:16:38.890
have to want to have
your ego dissolved.

01:16:38.890 --> 01:16:43.030
And that's his
superpower, right?

01:16:43.030 --> 01:16:46.100
Objectification of the other.

01:16:46.100 --> 01:16:49.235
So maybe you slip
it into his tea.

01:16:49.235 --> 01:16:51.110
But I don't think that's
going to work either

01:16:51.110 --> 01:16:54.940
because you really do have to
want what the experience is.

01:16:54.940 --> 01:16:56.750
So that's the dilemma.

01:16:56.750 --> 01:16:58.160
That's the dilemma where we are.

01:16:58.160 --> 01:17:00.830
I think it's highly relevant
to the kinds of questions

01:17:00.830 --> 01:17:03.120
we're facing.

01:17:03.120 --> 01:17:06.660
But exactly how you
get from here to there,

01:17:06.660 --> 01:17:08.990
that's a tough one.

01:17:08.990 --> 01:17:12.610
My next book, Rx for America.

01:17:12.610 --> 01:17:15.380
I want to thank all
of you for coming.

01:17:15.380 --> 01:17:18.190
I know there were a lot of
things going on this evening,

01:17:18.190 --> 01:17:20.630
and it's a very busy
time of the semester.

01:17:20.630 --> 01:17:23.389
I want to thank Elaine for
coming as a conversant.

01:17:23.389 --> 01:17:24.430
I want to thank you, too,

01:17:24.430 --> 01:17:26.110
And I want to thank
Michael as well

01:17:26.110 --> 01:17:28.880
for his fantastic contribution.

01:17:28.880 --> 01:17:30.010
Thank you, Robin.

01:17:30.010 --> 01:17:31.560
Thanks.

